{"id":"1608.08100","submitter":"George Mathew","authors":"George Mathew, Amritanshu Agrawal, Tim Menzies","title":"Finding Trends in Software Research","comments":"12 pages, 4 tables, 11 figures, Accepted in IEEE Transactions on\n  Software Engineering 2018","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1109/TSE.2018.2870388","report-no":null,"categories":"cs.SE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This paper explores the structure of research papers in software engineering.\nUsing text mining, we study 35,391 software engineering (SE) papers from 34\nleading SE venues over the last 25 years. These venues were divided, nearly\nevenly, between conferences and journals. An important aspect of this analysis\nis that it is fully automated and repeatable. To achieve that automation, we\nused a stable topic modeling technique called LDADE that fully automates\nparameter tuning in LDA. Using LDADE, we mine 11 topics that represent much of\nthe structure of contemporary SE. The 11 topics presented here should not be\n\"set in stone\" as the only topics worthy of study in SE. Rather our goal is to\nreport that (a) text mining methods can detect large scale trends within our\ncommunity; (b) those topic change with time; so (c) it is important to have\nautomatic agents that can update our understanding of our community whenever\nnew data arrives.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 29 Aug 2016 15:17:09 GMT"},{"version":"v10","created":"Wed, 3 Oct 2018 01:42:46 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 30 Aug 2016 01:34:40 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 10 Jan 2017 04:05:43 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Sat, 14 Jan 2017 02:22:51 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Fri, 7 Jul 2017 20:35:03 GMT"},{"version":"v6","created":"Thu, 5 Apr 2018 04:35:03 GMT"},{"version":"v7","created":"Mon, 3 Sep 2018 08:05:52 GMT"},{"version":"v8","created":"Mon, 17 Sep 2018 03:13:47 GMT"},{"version":"v9","created":"Tue, 18 Sep 2018 01:29:48 GMT"}],"update_date":